# Feature Documentation Template

## Feature Name
<!Stock Tracking Benchmark Graphs>

## Feature Type
_Peripheral Feature_

## Description
This feature allows the user to quickly compare the return on their portfolio against that of the overall market using the top three most common benchmarks: the S&P 500, NASDAQ and DOW. There are two graphs. The first graph is located on the dashboard and shows overall market trends. The second graph is located in the portfolio tab and compares the percent change of each benchmark against the percent change of the user’s portfolio.

## User Problem Solved
While the user can invest in various stocks and see how much they are gaining or losing, there is no real indication of how well they are doing. By tracking the percentage change of each benchmark, the user can compare the changes in their portfolio to see what improvements can be made.

## How It Works
This feature uses an API key from Alphavantage to grab ETFs that track the stock price of each benchmark. That data is then graphed using code. On the dashboard, only the price of each benchmark is shown. However, on the portfolio page, the percent change is calculated using the same data and then graphed against the percent change of the user’s portfolio.

## Inputs
To use the graph on the dashboard, the user will navigate to the correct tab and select the stock benchmark they prefer from a drop down menu. The graph will then adjust accordingly. The user can also choose how far back they want the data to release.  
To use the graph in the portfolio, the user will navigate to the correct tab and select the stock benchmark they prefer from a drop down menu. The graph will then adjust accordingly. The user can also choose how far back they want the data to release.

## Outputs
This system produces an API response and a data output.

## Dependencies
This feature depends on having proper API keys to function. Additionally, comparing the percent change of the overall market against the percent change of the user’s portfolio requires the user to have a portfolio. 

## Configuration / Setup
This feature is automatically enabled upon installation. However, the user must have a portfolio if they wish to compare a percent change against the overall market. Thus, in order to fully utilize this feature, the user has to invest and have a portfolio. 

## Example Usage
If the user has a portfolio that is growing or decreasing its value, but doesn’t really know how well they are doing, then they can use this feature to compare their return against the overall market. Then, if the user is not performing to their standards, they can adjust accordingly.

